    "content": "Somali President Hassan Sheikh Mohamud delivered a strong condemnation of Israel during his July 1 Independence Day address, calling the country a threat to regional stability and urging Somalis to reject any normalization of diplomatic ties. His remarks, which circulated widely on social media, also criticized the breakaway region of Somaliland for pursuing closer relations with Israel and allegedly allowing an Israeli presence on its territory.\n\nMohamud's speech came amid growing international scrutiny of Israel's policies in the Middle East and its expanding diplomatic engagements in Africa. Somaliland, which declared independence from Somalia in 1991 but remains unrecognized internationally, has sought to strengthen ties with Israel as part of its broader push for recognition and economic partnerships.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, the president's comments highlight ongoing divisions within Somali society regarding foreign policy and national unity. Many diaspora members have strong opinions on the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, and Mohamud's stance may influence their views on Somalia's alignment with other Muslim-majority nations.\n\nThe address has sparked mixed reactions, with some praising the president's firm position while others critiquing the language used as overly harsh. Analysts note that the statement could complicate Somalia's relations with Western allies who support Israel, potentially affecting aid and investment.\n\nRead the original report from Somalia Guardian here: https://www.somaliguardian.com/news/somalia-news/somalia-president-slams-israel-evil-war-mongering-state/",
